<TITLE> Dhaka stocks continue to slide in opening trade </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 23 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka stocks continued their decline on opening Wednesday though turnover marked a significant rise during the midday sessions. Mutual funds, power, state run oil entities and banks were driving the day's trading. The market opened with a steep decline in the general index. It recovered losses after the second hour before falling again during the midday sessions. The DGEN or general index at 12.55 pm was down 42.65 points or 1.45 percent to 2883.35, while the DSI or all share price index fell 34.18 points or 1.38 percent to 2429.91. Turnover amounted to Tk 1.18 billion from trading of 5,548,249 shares. Losers outnumbered gainers 152 to 51 with some 16 issues holding steady. State-run Jamuna Oil emerged at the peak of the turnover board at 12.57 pm, selling down at Tk 355.30 from Tuesday's Tk 365. Meghna Petroleum, second in turnover, also fell to Tk 353.90 from Tk 374.40. Grameen Mutual Fund One rallied from the previous day's losses, selling at Tk 90.90 from Tk 91.10 at Tuesday's close. Market major BRAC Bank declined to Tk 1460 from Tuesday's closing price of Tk 1504.25. AB Bank was also selling down at Tk 2741 from Tk 2789. Among the other issues on the turnover board, NBL, Islami Bank, UCBL, Power Grid Company of Bangladesh and DESCO also lost. bdn
